    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition">
                <ab> 
                    <lb n="1"/><expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan> <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>.
                    <lb n="2"/><persName><name type="praenomen" key="Publius"><expan><abbr>P</abbr><ex>ublio</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Publilius">Publ<supplied reason="omitted">il</supplied>io</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Daus">Dao</name></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/> <persName><name type="praenomen" key="Publius"><expan><abbr>P</abbr><ex>ublius</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Publilius">Publilius</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Hilarus">Hilarus</name></persName>
                    <lb n="4"/>et <persName><name type="praenomen" key="Publius"><expan><abbr>P</abbr><ex>ublius</ex></expan></name> <name type="gentilicium" key="Publilius">Publilius</name> <name type="cognomen" key="Agathon">Agathon</name></persName> 
                    <lb n="5"/>patrono et fratri
                    <lb n="6"/>optimo et <persName><name type="gentilicium" key="Iunia">Iunia</name>
                    <lb n="7"/><name type="cognomen" key="Cosmias">Cosmias</name></persName> coniugi
                    <lb n="8"/>bene merenti
                    <lb n="9"/>fecerunt.
                </ab>
            </div>
            
            <div type="translation">
                <p>
                    <lb n="1"/>To the Divine Spirits. For Publius Publilius Daus. Publius Publilius Hilarus and Publius Publilius Agathon for their patron and best brother, Iunia Cosmias for her husband well deserving, made (this).
                </p>
            </div>

            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The inscription on the marble urn records that it was made for Publius Publilius Daus by Publius Publilius Hilarus, Publius Publilius Agathon, and Iunia Cosmias. 
                    Publius Publilius Hilarus and Publius Publilius Agathon refer to the deceased as their patrono et fratri. Since they both have the same praenomen and gentilicium 
                    as the deceased, and Hilarus is a Roman cognomen whereas Agathon is of Greek origin, these two men may have been ex-slaves freed by Publius Publilius Daus. The 
                    quality of the craftmanship, the material, and the well-executed inscription suggest that the urn was of a high quality and expensive, indicating that the three 
                    living individuals who commissioned it were of a higher economic status.</p>
            </div>
            
